      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey can u explain what a p-value of 0.04 actually means in a clinical trial? like if they are testing a new blood pressure med, does that number mean the drug is definitely working?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.04 in a clinical trial doesn't necessarily mean the new blood pressure med is \"definitely\" working. Instead, it indicates that the observed effect (e.g., a certain reduction in blood pressure) is unlikely to have occurred by chance, assuming the null hypothesis is true. A p-value is a statistical significance measure, and a p-value of 0.04 means that if there's no real effect, there's only a 4% chance of observing the results the trial saw or more extreme results by chance.",
      "source": "target",
